    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nI have encountered an issue when using Cython with a function that contains another function which accesses a variable from the outer function using the nonlocal keyword.\n\nWhen using cython.compile, which internally uses inline.cython_inline, the inline.get_body function removes the body of the inner function. As a result, the call to inline.unbound_symbols fails because the nonlocal variable is no longer valid without the outer function's scope.\n\nI believe this could be fixed by replacing inline.unbound_symbols(code) with unbound_symbols(orig_code) to preserve the scope of the outer function in the analysis.\n\nCould you please look into this issue?\n\nThank you!\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n```cython\n# example code\n@cython.compile\ndef f():\n\ta = 1\n\tdef g():\n\t\tnonlocal a\n\t\ta = 2\n\n```\n```bash\nError compiling Cython file:\n------------------------------------------------------------\n...\n\na = 1\ndef g():\n    nonlocal a\n    ^\n------------------------------------------------------------\n\n(tree fragment):4:4: no binding for nonlocal 'a' found\n```\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nno compilation errors\n\n### OS\n\nall\n\n### Python version\n\n3.13.1\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.1.0a1\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
